00:51:05.660 --> 00:51:07.980
AUDIENCE: So mostly what
we covered right now

00:51:07.980 --> 00:51:11.041
was how the science works.

00:51:11.041 --> 00:51:11.790
MICHAEL TAFT: Yes.

00:51:11.790 --> 00:51:13.720
AUDIENCE: In terms
of implementation,

00:51:13.720 --> 00:51:16.170
do you suggest something
done differently?

00:51:16.170 --> 00:51:18.720
So mindfulness
meditation mostly, today,

00:51:18.720 --> 00:51:21.000
focuses on the
breath or something

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:23.106
that you can just
pay attention to.

00:51:23.106 --> 00:51:23.980
MICHAEL TAFT: Uh-huh.

00:51:23.980 --> 00:51:27.290
AUDIENCE: Given that there is
an emotional context to it now,

00:51:27.290 --> 00:51:30.180
is there something else
you suggest or propose?

00:51:30.180 --> 00:51:30.930
MICHAEL TAFT: Yes.

00:51:30.930 --> 00:51:34.280
So honestly, the
only different thing

00:51:34.280 --> 00:51:37.840
is that instead of the emotional
body sensations associated

00:51:37.840 --> 00:51:42.090
with breathing, or the emotional
body sensations of a body scan,

00:51:42.090 --> 00:51:46.284
you're picking out the
sensations of emotion.

00:51:46.284 --> 00:51:48.450
And that's why I had you
do the thing of bringing up

00:51:48.450 --> 00:51:51.260
the anxiety or bringing
up the happiness

00:51:51.260 --> 00:51:56.060
so that you could learn to feel
what an emotional sensation

00:51:56.060 --> 00:51:57.156
feels like.

00:51:57.156 --> 00:51:59.030
And then I was saying,
out in the world, when

00:51:59.030 --> 00:52:02.640
you have those emotions,
let's say you get really happy

00:52:02.640 --> 00:52:03.410
one day.

00:52:03.410 --> 00:52:04.290
You're super happy.

00:52:04.290 --> 00:52:06.490
Just spend five
minutes or one minute

00:52:06.490 --> 00:52:10.010
or even 30 seconds and
tune into the feelings

00:52:10.010 --> 00:52:11.290
of the happiness in your body.

00:52:11.290 --> 00:52:15.910
So you begin to learn what
an emotion feels like.

00:52:15.910 --> 00:52:19.480
But then, after that,
you're doing the same things

00:52:19.480 --> 00:52:21.800
that you would do in any
other mindfulness, which

00:52:21.800 --> 00:52:25.120
is you accept those feelings
just the way they are.

00:52:25.120 --> 00:52:27.130
You don't try to change them.

00:52:27.130 --> 00:52:29.340
And as I mentioned,
you zero in really

00:52:29.340 --> 00:52:32.080
specifically on the
details of the feeling.

00:52:32.080 --> 00:52:35.710
So you would do that in a breath
meditation or a body sensation

00:52:35.710 --> 00:52:37.020
meditation anyway, right?

00:52:37.020 --> 00:52:39.380
You're going to
accept the feelings.

00:52:39.380 --> 00:52:41.620
And you're going to get
into the subtleties.

00:52:41.620 --> 00:52:44.460
You want to notice the fine
details, and in this case,

00:52:44.460 --> 00:52:47.990
the fine details of
emotions in your body.

00:52:47.990 --> 00:52:49.480
That's all it takes.

00:52:49.480 --> 00:52:52.110
Because after awhile, you'll
start feeling your feelings,

00:52:52.110 --> 00:52:55.060
like, a week before you
would have felt them before,

00:52:55.060 --> 00:52:58.190
or 10 minutes before you would
have noticed them before.

00:52:58.190 --> 00:53:00.530
And that makes all
the difference.

00:53:00.530 --> 00:53:03.530
That's building that gap
between stimulus and response.

00:53:03.530 --> 00:53:08.730
Suddenly, it's like, how those
people could have potentially

00:53:08.730 --> 00:53:11.090
noticed the bad decks earlier.

00:53:11.090 --> 00:53:12.380
Their body was noticing it.

00:53:12.380 --> 00:53:14.200
They're having a
stress response.

00:53:14.200 --> 00:53:16.910
If you know how to feel a
stress response, than you could,

00:53:16.910 --> 00:53:20.410
presumably, notice that
the decks were bad earlier.

00:53:20.410 --> 00:53:23.320
So just getting really good
at feeling the feelings

00:53:23.320 --> 00:53:26.080
and not trying to change them,
getting into the details,

00:53:26.080 --> 00:53:29.496
getting all sensitive,
changes your life.

00:53:29.496 --> 00:53:30.700
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:53:30.700 --> 00:53:33.650
Are you familiar with
trapped emotions?

00:53:33.650 --> 00:53:37.417
And can you give me an
insight in how mindful can

00:53:37.417 --> 00:53:38.805
help release a trapped emotion?

00:53:38.805 --> 00:53:40.180
MICHAEL TAFT: So
what do you mean

00:53:40.180 --> 00:53:41.670
by the term trapped emotion?

00:53:41.670 --> 00:53:43.170
AUDIENCE: Trapped
emotion is emotion

00:53:43.170 --> 00:53:45.770
that is physically
trapped in the human flesh

00:53:45.770 --> 00:53:48.570
by not dealing with it in time.

00:53:48.570 --> 00:53:50.510
And over time it
just gets trapped.

00:53:50.510 --> 00:53:53.110
I know for a fact that
that's a condition

00:53:53.110 --> 00:53:55.707
that we all are affected by.

00:53:55.707 --> 00:53:58.165
If you are familiar with that
or not, what you can tell me.

00:53:58.165 --> 00:53:59.030
MICHAEL TAFT: Yeah.

00:53:59.030 --> 00:54:03.370
What I would say is that
the main thing to do

00:54:03.370 --> 00:54:06.730
there is the acceptance piece.

00:54:06.730 --> 00:54:08.740
Because for something,
for an emotion

00:54:08.740 --> 00:54:11.460
to stay suppressed like
that, or stay trapped,

00:54:11.460 --> 00:54:14.190
it has to have a force
keeping it in there.

00:54:14.190 --> 00:54:17.020
It's being suppressed in
some way psychologically.

00:54:17.020 --> 00:54:19.030
But if you, over time--
through meditation

00:54:19.030 --> 00:54:20.880
and through mindfulness--
are reversing

00:54:20.880 --> 00:54:25.820
that psychological stance, and
accepting over and over what

00:54:25.820 --> 00:54:27.960
you're feeling, it might
be that you don't even

00:54:27.960 --> 00:54:30.400
feel that trapped
emotion for a long time.

00:54:30.400 --> 00:54:32.622
But then one day, because
you're insula's growing

00:54:32.622 --> 00:54:35.080
and you're getting much more
sensitive, much more detailed.

00:54:35.080 --> 00:54:37.209
You notice, hey, I'm
feeling something in there.

00:54:37.209 --> 00:54:38.500
I'm feeling something in there.

00:54:38.500 --> 00:54:40.210
And it might not feel very good.

00:54:40.210 --> 00:54:40.710
Right?

00:54:40.710 --> 00:54:42.335
There's a reason
you're suppressing it.

00:54:42.335 --> 00:54:44.720
It might feel really awful.

00:54:44.720 --> 00:54:47.790
But you just keep accepting
it and accepting it.

00:54:47.790 --> 00:54:50.530
And eventually, it
will start to express.

00:54:50.530 --> 00:54:53.300
It's why you have to have
this stance of acceptance.

00:54:53.300 --> 00:54:55.830
Because you want those
kind of suppressed emotions

00:54:55.830 --> 00:54:58.770
to express and
then be done with.

00:54:58.770 --> 00:55:01.320
Be done with them.

00:55:01.320 --> 00:55:02.900
AUDIENCE: So I do
a lot of training

00:55:02.900 --> 00:55:04.760
on my team around feedback.

00:55:04.760 --> 00:55:07.180
And when I say that
word, everyone's

00:55:07.180 --> 00:55:09.095
like, morale just
drops considerably.

00:55:09.095 --> 00:55:12.601
It has a very visceral,
emotional response.

00:55:12.601 --> 00:55:14.850
And I train them using almost
the exact same technique

00:55:14.850 --> 00:55:16.040
that you did
around, like, almost

00:55:16.040 --> 00:55:17.230
like immunizing yourself.

00:55:17.230 --> 00:55:19.749
So I'm going to
purposely apply pressure

00:55:19.749 --> 00:55:21.790
so that you can feel what
this feels like, to get

00:55:21.790 --> 00:55:22.998
like the worst possible news.

00:55:22.998 --> 00:55:24.900
So if you see it again
you won't feel as bad.

00:55:24.900 --> 00:55:25.780
MICHAEL TAFT: Yeah.

00:55:25.780 --> 00:55:27.370
AUDIENCE: Do you have
any other suggestions

00:55:27.370 --> 00:55:29.180
I can give my teammates
when I train them

00:55:29.180 --> 00:55:32.190
on this kind of
behavioral response?

00:55:32.190 --> 00:55:35.220
MICHAEL TAFT: Suggestions
for making it--

00:55:35.220 --> 00:55:36.430
AUDIENCE: I guess, bearable?

00:55:36.430 --> 00:55:37.220
Tolerable.

00:55:37.220 --> 00:55:39.780
It's a painful process,
especially here.

00:55:39.780 --> 00:55:41.220
Feedback can be really intense.

00:55:41.220 --> 00:55:42.053
MICHAEL TAFT: Right.

00:55:42.053 --> 00:55:43.650
So I'm sure, as
you already know,

00:55:43.650 --> 00:55:46.560
starting out with small emotions
is better than starting out

00:55:46.560 --> 00:55:47.590
with big ones.

00:55:47.590 --> 00:55:48.090
Right?

00:55:48.090 --> 00:55:50.510
Little tiny discomforts,
emotionally,

00:55:50.510 --> 00:55:52.200
are much easier to work with.

00:55:52.200 --> 00:55:55.330
The other one is-- and I
mean, this is not necessarily

00:55:55.330 --> 00:55:58.970
making it easier--
but you know, it's

00:55:58.970 --> 00:56:02.400
different in your
lab or your office

00:56:02.400 --> 00:56:04.780
than it is out in the world.

00:56:04.780 --> 00:56:07.600
And so it's something
you can give them

00:56:07.600 --> 00:56:10.410
on the first day is
just to say, hey,

00:56:10.410 --> 00:56:12.710
we're not going to trigger
you emotionally here.

00:56:12.710 --> 00:56:15.060
But between the
time you see me now

00:56:15.060 --> 00:56:18.860
and the time you see me next,
when something triggers you

00:56:18.860 --> 00:56:22.350
and you feel bad emotionally,
here's what you do.

00:56:22.350 --> 00:56:26.620
So that it's allowing
the world to give them

00:56:26.620 --> 00:56:28.125
the difficult experience.

00:56:28.125 --> 00:56:29.500
But now you've
given them the way

00:56:29.500 --> 00:56:31.250
to work with it, to
begin working with it.

00:56:31.250 --> 00:56:33.450
And then when they come
back the next to the office,

00:56:33.450 --> 00:56:37.020
they have material that you've
already given them a tool

00:56:37.020 --> 00:56:39.422
to help them cope with that

00:56:39.422 --> 00:56:42.140
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

00:56:42.140 --> 00:56:44.030
MICHAEL TAFT: So thank
you all very much.

00:56:44.030 --> 00:56:47.390
And hope to speak to you again.

